statement.p:
Determine the following limits, if possible.


\displaystyle \lim_{n \to \infty} 3+\frac{5}{2^n}

\displaystyle \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{n^2-3n}{5n-1}

\displaystyle \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{1+2^n}{3+5^n}

li.p:
The problem can be solved up if we just factor out from the numerator and denominator
the dominant term (greatest power) and simplify as needed.

  \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{n^2-3n}{5n-1} & = \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{n^2(1-\frac{3}{n})}{n(5-\frac{1}{n})} 
   & = \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{n(1-\frac{3}{n})}{5-\frac{1}{n}} 
   & = \frac{+\infty \cdot(1-\frac{3}{\infty})}{5-\frac{1}{\infty}}
   & = \frac{+\infty\cdot 1}{5} = +\infty.

solution.p:
To compute the explicit formula for the summation,
we need to remember that the variable n is a constant with respect to the summation index k.
We will rewrite the formula of the sequence in summation to be a sum
so that we can use the linearity property.

  \sum_{k=1}^{n} \Big(1+\frac{3k}{n}\Big) \cdot \frac{3}{n} &= \sum_{k=1}^{n}  \frac{3}{n} + \frac{9k}{n^2}
   &= \frac{3}{n} \cdot \sum_{k=1}^{n} 1 + \frac{9}{n^2} \cdot \sum_{k=1}^{n} k
   &= \frac{3}{n} \cdot n + \frac{9}{n^2} \cdot \frac{n(n+1)}{2}
   &= 3 + \frac{9(n+1)}{2n}
   &= 3 + \frac{9n+9}{2n}

We see that the summation is itself a sequence involving an index n.
We find the limit of that sequence.
The fraction \displaystyle \frac{9n+9}{2n} will be indeterminate form \frac{\infty}{\infty},
so we will factor out the dominant term of n from top and bottom.

  \lim_{n \to \infty} \sum_{k=1}^{n} \Big(1+\frac{3k}{n}\Big) \cdot \frac{3}{n} &= \lim_{n \to \infty} 3 + \frac{9n+9}{2n}
   &= \lim_{n \to \infty} 3 + \frac{n(9+\frac{9}{n})}{2n}
   &= \lim_{n \to \infty} 3 + \frac{9}{2}+\frac{9}{2n}
   &= 3 + \frac{9}{2}+\frac{9}{\infty}
   &= 3 + \frac{9}{2}+0 
   &= \frac{15}{2} = 7 \frac{1}{2}
